FAMILY 1: Browser Trust Signals (collectBrowserTrustSignals)
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Asks: does this request look like it came from a real browser a real
person is using right now?

  Rule ID                        │ Score │ Trigger
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  automated_user_agent           │  +45  │ UA contains python-requests, curl,
                                 │       │ wget, go-http-client, axios,
                                 │       │ postman, phantomjs, headlesschrome
  headless_browser_signature     │  +35  │ UA contains 'headlesschrome'
  phantomjs_signature            │  +40  │ UA contains 'phantomjs'
  missing_browser_origin_referer │  +28  │ Browser-like UA on auth/engagement
                                 │       │ path with no Origin or Referer
  origin_mismatch                │  +35  │ Origin ≠ configured frontend host
                                 │       │ and ≠ localhost
  sec_fetch_mode_suspicious      │  +12  │ Sec-Fetch-Mode not cors/same-origin
                                 │       │ /navigate
  sec_fetch_mode_missing         │   +8  │ Sec-Fetch-Mode header absent
  sec_fetch_site_suspicious      │  +22  │ Sec-Fetch-Site not same-origin/site
  sec_fetch_site_missing         │  +10  │ Sec-Fetch-Site header absent
  sec_ch_ua_missing              │  +12  │ Sec-CH-UA absent on browser UA
  accept_language_missing        │   +8  │ Accept-Language absent

  Key insight: these signals are cheap to spoof individually but expensive
  to spoof completely. An attacker who nails the user-agent but forgets
  Sec-CH-UA and Accept-Language still scores into challenge or block range
  before touching any rate limit.

FAMILY 2: Honeypot Field Detection
────────────────────────────────────
  Rule ID                │ Score │ Trigger
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  honeypot_field_filled  │  +95  │ Any of: website, homepage, companyUrl,
                         │       │ referralUrl present and non-empty in body

  These fields exist in the frontend request schema but are never shown
  to users and never filled by legitimate frontend code. A bot that
  auto-fills forms triggers this on first contact and immediately crosses
  the block threshold (95 ≥ 90).

FAMILY 3: IP Rate Tracking
───────────────────────────
  Rule ID           │ Score │ Trigger
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  ip_rate_exceeded  │  +35  │ Hits from this IP in the rolling window
                    │       │ exceed the profile threshold

  State stored simultaneously in:
  • In-process Map<string, number[]> — fast, zero network latency
  • Redis INCR+EXPIRE at key: bot-defense:ip:<key> — shared across
    all API pod replicas, survives restarts

FAMILY 4: Device Fingerprint Rate Tracking
───────────────────────────────────────────
  Rule ID               │ Score │ Trigger
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  device_rate_exceeded  │  +30  │ Hits from this device hash exceed
                        │       │ the profile threshold

  Fingerprint = SHA-256(userAgent|language|timezone|screenResolution|colorDepth)
  Redis key: bot-defense:device:<hash>

  Why this matters: IP rotation is cheap. VPN and proxy farms cycle IPs
  constantly. Device fingerprints are harder to rotate because they require
  changing the full browser environment. A bot farm that rotates IPs but
  reuses the same browser profile is caught at the device layer.

FAMILY 5: Payload Repetition Detection
───────────────────────────────────────
  Rule ID                     │ Score │ Trigger
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  payload_repetition_exceeded │  +25  │ Same SHA-256(path+body) appears
                              │  +45  │ more than threshold (×2 threshold)
                              │       │ times in the rolling window

  Redis key: bot-defense:payload:<sha256hex>
  Catches: credential stuffing, automated OAuth probing, scripted
  repeated-action bots hitting the same endpoint with identical bodies.

