The core middleware is a single Express function. Drop it before your route
handlers. Configure four environment variables. You're running.

  FCG_BOT_DEFENSE_LICENSE_KEY        your issued key
  FCG_BOT_DEFENSE_LICENSE_SECRET     your issued secret
  BOT_DEFENSE_EXPECTED_HOSTNAME      your production API hostname
  BOT_DEFENSE_VERBOSE_LOGS           true|false

The bridge is optional but is where the real industry value lives. Connect
via HMAC-authenticated webhooks, start ingesting signals from your platform,
receive policy decisions, close the enforcement loop. The more platforms on
the bridge, the richer the collective signal corpus — and every platform
benefits from every other platform's observations in real time.

The Redis layer is plug-and-play. Provide a REDIS_URL. Without Redis it
falls back to in-process counters that still enforce thresholds correctly.
The system is stateless at the edge, scales horizontally with no coordination
overhead, and fails open — a Redis failure means enforcement falls back to
in-process, not that your API goes down.

The entire system is readable TypeScript. Every signal family is explicit.
Every score weight is a literal number in source code. Every threshold is
configurable. No black boxes. No third-party dependency for the core
detection logic. Any engineer who can read this document can implement,
adopt, extend, and improve this system.


